{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8953ac72-1388-41e1-bcf1-2ec54a310271","content":"The project doesn't exist yet in this workspace, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using `stdio` transport:\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — runs `dotnet run --project <path>` to start your server.\n- Your C# server must use the **stdio transport** (not HTTP/SSE). If you're using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package, that's typically `.WithStdioServerTransport()`.\n\n**If using a published/built binary instead**, point directly to it:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"exec\", \"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Debug/net8.0/MyMcpServer.dll\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nYou can also add `\"env\"` for environment variables if needed. Once saved, VS Code will detect the server and list its tools in Copilot agent mode.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"76cf39df-eb69-4881-b678-2b92728a7c39","outputTokens":377,"requestId":"8424:2A1B2F:193E9D:20CA91:69FFDAC0"},"id":"109c357b-d83c-46b9-9c78-eedb70e7c842","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:09:29.433Z","parentId":"6695e164-0691-4696-b2f3-8ea1e3a58efc"}
